<div id="review_1756001136" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1756001136" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25882000-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1436707093p2/25882000.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1756001136?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/25882000-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25882000-joe?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1756001136" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2284155855378682187">The author follows up her engaging debut, Dust and Shadow, with The Gods Of Gotham. The setting is 1845 Manhattan and the early days of the NYPD. Our hero, Timothy Wilde, loses his barkeep job – and almost his life – after a devastating fire. Through political connections – and his brother – - Timothy joins the Police Department. This “intro” taking more than a few pages to get through and a chronic problem I found with this book. For although the detail here – which I can only assume is the fru</span>
  <span id="freeText2284155855378682187" style="display:none">The author follows up her engaging debut, Dust and Shadow, with The Gods Of Gotham. The setting is 1845 Manhattan and the early days of the NYPD. Our hero, Timothy Wilde, loses his barkeep job – and almost his life – after a devastating fire. Through political connections – and his brother – - Timothy joins the Police Department. This “intro” taking more than a few pages to get through and a chronic problem I found with this book. For although the detail here – which I can only assume is the fruit of extensive research – is excellent, there is just too much of it, to the detriment of the story itself.<br /><br />The central plot/story is an interesting one. After joining the force and while patrolling what is now lower Manhattan, Timothy encounters a distraught young girl – she actually stumbles into him - covered in blood. Although unharmed it becomes clear the child was witness to a brutal and harrowing crime, which after much patience on our hero’s part – the young girl has a little difficulty in actually telling her story – is just the tip of a nefarious iceberg – for it seems a child serial killer is running rampant on the streets of NY. (Although this criminal seems more 20th or 21st Century that 19th, this is not in and of itself a show-stopper.)<br /><br />Timothy, with his law enforcement cohorts, begins investigating and things then turn ugly – not only in what they “uncover” but also with the delving into the NY underworld and holding city politics at bay. The supporting cast here is more than functional, including Timothy’s brother, his boss, a wizened old veteran of the force, a conniving madame, a doctor and even the young girl. (Timothy’s love interest on the other hand - not so much.) And even the puzzle, although convoluted, is a good one. Unfortunately, for me, the wealth of historic detail, particularly the flash, or slang of the time, was just too much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2284155855378682187" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


