    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3636290741" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3636290741" />
    <a title="Brian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1111042-brian"><img alt="Brian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567183757p2/1111042.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3636290741?book_show_action=true">Nov 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian" href="/user/show/1111042-brian">Brian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12775243-the-gods-of-gotham">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=kindle">kindle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=new-york">new-york</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3636290741" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer754890314651872424">I really enjoyed this book and had a hard time putting it down. The story is engaging, and the characters are vivid. <br/><br/>The story takes place in New York City in 1845. The narrator, Timothy Wilde, is a young bartender who loses his home, his job, and part of his face when a huge explosion and fire destroy several blocks of the city. On the recommendation of his politically connected older brother, he reluctantly accepts an appointment as a “copper star” on New York’s new police force.<br/><br/>Life for many </span>
  <span id="freeText754890314651872424" style="display:none">I really enjoyed this book and had a hard time putting it down. The story is engaging, and the characters are vivid. <br /><br />The story takes place in New York City in 1845. The narrator, Timothy Wilde, is a young bartender who loses his home, his job, and part of his face when a huge explosion and fire destroy several blocks of the city. On the recommendation of his politically connected older brother, he reluctantly accepts an appointment as a “copper star” on New York’s new police force.<br /><br />Life for many New Yorkers is not easy. As Timothy notes, “Crime is rampant, robbery expected, assault common, murder often unsolved.” Prostitution, including child prostitution, is also pervasive, especially in the notorious Five Points and surrounding areas. And due to the potato famine in Ireland, Irish immigrants are arriving by the boatload and the population is exploding. Many of the natives, politically aligned with the Whigs, are virulently anti-immigrant and anti-Catholic, and when they aren’t blaming the Irish for everything that goes wrong, they blame the Blacks.<br /><br />Just two weeks into his job as a copper star, Timothy is on his way home at night when he collides on the street with a little Irish girl who is covered in blood. Instead of taking her to the station house, he gives her shelter at this boarding house. He soon learns that the girl, who calls herself “Bird,” is a runaway “kinchin mab”—a child prostitute. The next day, the police chief sends him to investigate the murder of a young boy whose mutilated body has been discovered in a trash barrel. Suspecting that there is a connection between this boy and Bird, Timothy begins to investigate and soon finds himself immersed in the sordid world of child prostitution and murder.<br /><br />Readers are also exposed to this world, of course, as we accompany Timothy in his investigation. But although the story has the potential to be depressing, I found it fascinating. Maybe I’m just inured to these kinds of stories as someone who reads a fair bit of true crime and mystery fiction, but I also think the fact that the story is set almost 200 years ago gives it some distance from the reader. <br /><br />Author Lyndsay Faye has done a masterful job of researching and recreating New York in 1845—the geography, the social conditions, the look and feel of the streets, the clothing, and most impressively to me, the language, notably including the “flash” terminology of criminals and lower classes. This attention to detail resulted in a very immersive reading experience that quickly hooked me and kept me interested all the way through. It’s quite a brilliant book, in my opinion.</span>
  <a data-text-id="754890314651872424" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review3636290741">
  <td colspan="2">
